Package tradedatacorp.smelter.lexical.binary

Class Original

java.lang.Object
tradedatacorp.smelter.lexical.binary.Original
All Implemented Interfaces:
BinaryLexical<StickDouble>, Lexical
public class Original extends Object implements BinaryLexical<StickDouble>
A BinaryLexical implementation for translating StickDouble instances into binary arrays.

This class is designed to efficiently convert StickDouble instances into boolean arrays that represent their binary form. Each instance of this class is tied to a specific ticker symbol and a single time interval, ensuring precise and consistent translations. This classes primary focus is to prepare a binary file reader for accurate and efficient reading rather than maximum write speed. A file write should be able to write pretty fast if certain meta information is known beforehand.

The state of the lexical primarily consists of the Header and the Data. The Header represents the meta data about all the data, including how many data points are stored and how long each field is. The Header is split into 2 parts H1 and H2. H1 contains all fixed bit lengths but values may change. H2 consists of variable bit lengths based on different dependencies. The Data consists of many Stick data points. The details about each stick attributes are in the Header fields. The Header and the Data make up the Content of this BinaryLexical. This class is not meant to hold an entire large file all at once. It is meant to hold portions of Content such that a file writer can write portions of a full file at a time.

When a Lexical reads valid Content for the first time, it is exptected to read from left to right: H1, H2, data elements. The Lexical knows the exact length of H1 and each of it's static fields. H2 bit lengths and values will be known based on the value of H1 Fields. The Data will be known based on all the Header data. Such as the bit size of each data point and all of it's attributes.

Below is a table representing the Header

Header Fields
FieldBit LengthFull NameDescription
h1_byid1By IDMay not be needed anymore.
h1_int25Time Frame IntervalThe unsigned integer value represents the number of seconds for the time frame.
h1_ct_len26Data Count Bit LengthThe unsigned integer value represents number of bits for field h2_data_ct.

Single Datapint TBA
